{[show S]Partner opened, you responded a new suit, and partner bid a third suit; holding a strong five-five hand you bid the fourth suit to force to game, then set diamonds and probed for slam. Partner opens 1\D.
[BID 1H] ⟦You respond 1\H, showing four or more hearts; you hold five hearts alongside five diamonds.⟧ Partner rebids 2\C, a second suit — three suits are now on the table.
[BID 2S] ⟦You bid the fourth suit, 2\S — Fourth Suit Forcing, artificial and game-forcing, not a real spade suit, asking partner to keep describing.⟧ Partner bids 2NT, showing a spade stopper.
[BID 4D] ⟦Instead of settling in notrump you jump to 4\D, agreeing diamonds and showing genuine slam interest in the five-five hand. [ACCEPT 5N]⟧ Partner cue-bids 4\S, showing the spade control and cooperating toward slam.
[BID 4N] ⟦You bid 4\N, Roman Keycard Blackwood for diamonds, asking how many keycards partner holds.⟧ Partner answers 5\D — zero or three keycards; since partner opened and cue-bid, zero is impossible, so it is three.
[BID 6D] ⟦Counting partner's three keycards with your two aces gives all five; without confirmation of anything more you settle in the small slam, 6\D.⟧
[show NESW]All five keycards were present and 6\D rolled home thirteen tricks — the grand was in fact cold. Signing off was the safe choice given the ambiguous reply, though a king-ask toward 7\D was defensible once you knew partner could not hold zero.}
