{[show S]You opened, then showed a second suit; partner bid the fourth suit to force to game, and once a heart fit appears you must decide how high to drive.
[BID 1D] ⟦You open one\D with your good five-card diamond suit.⟧ Partner responds one\H, showing four or more hearts.
[BID 1S] ⟦Over partner's one\H you bid one\S, showing your four spades.⟧ Partner bids the fourth suit, two\C, Fourth Suit Forcing and game-going, asking for more.
[BID 2D] ⟦You rebid two\D to show the extra diamond length and your unbalanced shape.⟧ Partner bids three\H, revealing a strong six-card heart suit.
[BID 4N] ⟦With three aces and a fitting hand you take charge and bid four\N, Roman Keycard Blackwood for hearts.⟧ Partner shows two keycards plus the queen of trumps.
[BID 5N] ⟦That accounts for every keycard, so you ask for kings with five\N.⟧ Partner shows one king.
[BID 7H] ⟦Holding all five keycards, the trump queen, and a side king, you gamble the grand in seven\H. [ACCEPT 6H]⟧
[show NESW]Every top card was present, so seven\H was a reasonable shot, but the hand needed a break that did not come and it fell one short for twelve tricks. Settling for six\H was the safer road; on this layout both readings were sound and only the distribution decided it.}
