{[show S]Partner opened, you responded a new suit, and partner bid a third suit; holding a five-five hand with a diamond void you bid the fourth suit to force to game, then showed both majors. Partner opens 1\D.
[BID 1S] ⟦You respond 1\S, showing four or more spades; you hold five spades and five hearts with a diamond void.⟧ Partner rebids 2\C, a second suit — three suits are now on the table.
[BID 2H] ⟦You bid the fourth suit, 2\H — Fourth Suit Forcing, artificial and game-forcing, asking partner to keep describing before you reveal your shape.⟧ Partner rebids 3\D, showing extra diamond length rather than spade support or a heart guard.
[BID 4H] ⟦With your void in partner's long suit, notrump is unappealing; you bid 4\H to show the genuine second major and offer a choice of major-suit games.⟧ Reading you for five-five, partner returns to your first suit, 4\S.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 4\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NESW]Showing the second major let partner steer into the eight-card spade fit, and 4\S brought home eleven tricks. With a void opposite partner's long diamonds, staying in a major was far better than notrump.}
